Reason: Acetic acid consists of a methyl group attached to a carboxyl group (COOH). Starting from a base molecule like methane, which has a melting point of -182.5 degrees Celsius, the introduction of functional groups will substantially modify this value. The methyl group slightly increases the melting point due to an increase in molecular weight and size. However, the significant change comes from the carboxyl group, which, due to its ability to form hydrogen bonds, will substantially increase the melting point. For instance, formic acid (HCOOH), with one less carbon, has a melting point of 8.4 degrees Celsius.
